projects.title: Brazil Synchromodality
projects.description:
Brazil is one the fastest growing countries in terms of economy. The state of Mato Grosso, located in the centre-west region, is one of the biggest states in the country and is the leading producer in the country’s agricultural sector. With respectively soybeans, corn, cotton, and cattle as its primary export commodities within this sector, the state of Mato Grosso has a large contribution in the national export. Nonetheless, at the same time, the transportation costs from the state’s crop fields are raising sky high due to inefficiency in the process. Main problems in the export transportation process are the unpaved roads, excessive use of trucks, and the incompleteness of multimodal routes. 
The Dutch consortium, consisting of: TNO, Panteia/NEA, Scheepvaart en Transport College  (STC), Expertise en Innovatie Centrum Binnenvaart (EICB), and Connekt, has commissioned the University of Applied Sciences in Amsterdam to map the Mato Grosso Corridor. This project included a field research programme in Brasilia (DF) and the Mato Grosso corridor. Eventually, one of these corridors will be further developed into a blueprint, which will include all information and application methods to develop this corridor.
I have been involved in the mapping process in Brasília (DF) and Cuiabá. In order to enhance our research, I have presented several meetings with Brazilian expert teams (ANTT, ANTAQ, CNI, SEP) and the Ministry of Transport. Our research resulted in four export routes to northern ports, which are considered as most likely and feasible.

projects.title: Whitepaper Taipei Taoyuan International Airport
projects.description: In contrast with the previous projects, this project was an individual project. Each individual had the task to write a white paper on the effects of an airport master plan written by another team. The aim of this project was to write a white paper from a stakeholder’s perspective, which could be: inhabitants, airline, and governments. The master plan of Taipei Taoyuan International Airport was assigned to me. I had to write a white paper from an airline’s perspective. The focus of my white paper was to expose the importance of low-cost airlines for Taipei Taoyuan International Airport. It was written from an airline’s perspective.

projects.title: A new aircraft type for KLM
projects.description:
KLM is the biggest airline in the Netherlands and together with Air France, one of the biggest airlines in the world. KLM is dealing with an increasing competition and therefore constantly looking for innovative and smart ideas to achieve competitive advantage. Several airlines, including Emirates, are already using the Airbus A380-800. By using an aircraft that is able to transport a high volume of passengers, airlines become a serious threat for KLM. The research is fictional and part of the Aviation Logistics course at the Amsterdam University. This research was conducted together with six other Aviation Logistics students.
After an extensive research, the project group and I came to the conclusion to give a positive advise to KLM, regarding the implementation of the Airbus A380-800 in their current network and fleet mix (2011-2012). After analyzing the KLM and SkyTeam network, the advise was given to use the A380 on the route Amsterdam-Atlanta, as Atlanta is the largest hub and home base for Delta Airlines, which gives passenger a wide variety of hinterland connections.

projects.title: Airport Consultancy
projects.description:
O.R. Tambo International Airport is the main-hub airport in South Africa and has the ambition to be the largest airport of the continent with reference to the passenger amounts, cargo amount and aircraft movements. The airport will have to expand in the upcoming twenty years, due to several capacity bottlenecks, to able to handle the expected growth in air traffic. By creating a master plan for Airports Company South Africa by the project group, a follow-up of the previous project, the company has the possibility to realize the expansions of the airport. Thereby, the future strategy should be taken into account as it is required to stimulate the region economically to enable the airport and its region to grow continuously.

The project group based their advice on the current strategy of Airports Company South Africa: to build an efficient and customer focused world-leading airport business, parallel to the vision to empower and sustain South African communities. The main recommendation is to stay innovative, efficient, flexible, socially involved with the surrounding communities and companies, and constantly revise the forecasts and market position of the airport. Forecasts indicated that the total passenger amounts will be over 37 million in the year 2032 and the aircraft demand peak will be 71 aircraft movements on the busiest day in the year 2032. New infrastructure and expansions are required in order to be able to handle the demand.

Gaining competitive advantage is an important factor to stay ahead of regional competitors and, including the increasing globalization, international competitors. Investing in expansions of the airport will have benefits for the entire region. The expansions will lead to more jobs for the city region, which will lead to economic growth as well. In the end, answers are given to four main factors the airport has to deal with during the expansion phases: the social, political, environmental and economic factors.

projects.title: Airport Layout
projects.description: Oliver Reginald Tambo International airport Johannesburg is the main hub-airport in South Africa and the busiest on the continent. However, there is a limit to the capacity of the airport, while the demand for air traffic is increasing. The project groups of Aviation Logistics had been asked by Netherlands Airport Consultants B.V. to create a master plan up to 2032 with a durable future perspective. The focus of the master plan is on the expansion of the capacity by designing a land-use plan taking into account a new ten million passenger-terminal and one or two new runways. Since the master plan will take more than seven weeks a start of the master plan had been made together with a land-use plan. This implied an extensive market research, a twenty-year forecast and a functional design of a passenger terminal expansion.

projects.title: Supply Chain Avio-Diepen
projects.description:
Avio-Diepen has a strong position in the world being a spare parts distributor. In order to maintain this position, the project group was asked by Avio-Diepen to optimize their supply chain. One of the goals of the project is delivering a new design of the supply chain of Avio-Diepen, taking into account the growing markets in the world with the focus on Atlanta, Hong Kong and Alphen aan den Rijn. The second objective is delivering a cost calculation model for the correct allocation of transport costs between the different links in the supply chain of Avio-Diepen. The delivery of a business plan for Avio-Diepen is included.

The report will lead to an answer on the following question: ‘How can the supply chain of Avio-Diepen be optimized, taking into account the growing markets in the world with the focus on Atlanta, Alphen aan den Rijn and Hong Kong?’ The final recommendations of the project group are related to the Incoterms; Value and packaging tool; and Information Systems.

projects.title: Catchment Area
projects.description: In the figures and reports it is visible that London’s air traffic has been divided into six airports near London. This is caused by the growth and popularity of the city. To be able to visualize which airport the passengers choose and what suppliers on the airports are involved, the catchment area and creation of several business models are needed. The main objective is to visualize the catchment area and the active suppliers on three London airports: London City Airport, London Heathrow and London Stansted. The project group is going to research the catchment area and suppliers of the three London airports.

projects.title: Road to seventy MB
projects.description: Amsterdam Airport Schiphol (AMS) is the biggest airport of the Netherlands and is an important hub with a broad range of destinations. The airport is an important hub for transfer passengers, which has its impact on the baggage handling system. The intention of the project was to analyze the airport’s baggage handling system and see when the system will reach it’s capacity, and how the system can be optimized. One of the main goals of AMS is to be able to process seventy million bags in the future. By using a trend forecast, it became clear when AMS will reach its main goal. The research requires an extensive analysis of all involved segments such as: hold baggage systems, check-in counters, fulltime equivalents, drop-off points and automatic check-in counters. The research shows that there will be a shortage of check in desks in the upcoming years due to an increasing amount in passenger rates. A break-even analysis shows that it will be more costly efficient to use automatic drop off points in the coming three years.

projects.title: The turn around process
projects.description: The intention of this project was to observe the several processes at an airport, especially processes to complete an aircraft’s Turn Around Process (TAP). For this project I have cooperate with eight other Aviation Logistics students. We observed and analyze eight different TAP’s at Amsterdam Airport Schiphol (AMS). These observations were conducted to explore the difference between aircraft types, destinations and airlines. A specific research was conducted on the cargo layout of Menzies Aviation at AMS. The integral logistic concept was used to describe their strategy, logistical objectives, basic structure, controlling system, information streams, staff organization and their key performance indicators.
